ing a graph based on a product that takes 100 hours for the first unit, with an 80% learning curve applied.\"", "\"LEARNING CURVE FORMULA QUIZ\":\"A quiz that involves calculating the time it will take to produce the seventh unit of a new product, given that it takes 500 hours to produce the first unit and workers have a 95% learning effect.\"", "\"LABOUR COST QUIZ\":\"A quiz that involves calculating the budgeted labor cost for a new business, McSporran, which is producing kilts with an 85% learning effect applied.\"", "\"LEAST SQUARES REGRESSION METHOD\":", "\"STEADY STATE\":\"Steady state is achieved when the incremental time per unit is constant. Even after steady state is reached, the cumulative average time per unit would still be decreasing.\"", "\"QUIZ: LEARNING CURVE AND STEADY STATE\":\"This quiz involves calculating the labour time per unit for the 30th and subsequent units and the total labour time to make the first 100 units of the XY123 model, considering a learning rate of 85%.\"", "\"LEARNING RATE\":The \"Learning Rate\" refers to the rate at which workers improve their efficiency and reduce the time taken to complete tasks as they gain experience. It is a measure of how quickly production efficiency improves as more units are produced. Specifically, it indicates the rate at which labour time per unit decreases as workers become more efficient with experience. In the context of Bokco, a 90% learning rate was initially used, meaning that the time taken to produce a unit decreases by 10% with each doubling of the number of units produced. However, an engineer later suggested an 85% learning rate, indicating a more rapid improvement in efficiency.", "\"LABOUR TIME FOR THE 30TH AND SUBSEQUENT UNITS\":\"Labour time for the 30th and subsequent units is calculated as the difference between the total time taken to make the first 30 units and the total time taken to make the first 29 units, resulting in 0.347 hours.\"", "\"TOTAL LABOUR TIME FOR THE FIRST 100 UNITS\":\"Total labour time for the first 100 units is calculated as the sum of the total time taken to make the first 30 units and the time taken to make the next 70 units, resulting in 37.80 hours.\"", "\"ESTIMATING THE LEARNING RATE\":\"Estimating the learning rate involves using a tabular approach based on production to date and the time taken, especially when cumulative units are given in exponentials of 2. The learning rate stops when the incremental time per unit becomes constant.\"", "\"QUIZ: LEARNING RATE\":\"This quiz involves calculating the learning rate that applied to the new PC and estimating the point at which the learning period finishes, based on the incremental time taken for each unit.\"", "\"END OF THE LEARNING PERIOD\":\"The learning period ends when the incremental time per unit becomes constant. In this case, the learning effect ends after the 8th unit, as the time taken per unit becomes constant at 120.5 minutes from the 9th to the 16th unit.\"", "\"ALGEBRAIC APPROACH TO LEARNING RATE\":\"An algebraic approach is used to determine the learning rate when only cumulative average time information is available for two levels of output that are not exponentials of 2. This method involves solving for the learning rate using algebraic equations.\"", "\"EXAMPLE OF ALGEBRAIC APPROACH TO LEARNING RATE\":\"This example demonstrates the algebraic approach to calculate the learning rate. The first unit took 300 minutes, and the total time for the first 8 units was 2,056 minutes, resulting in a cumulative average time of 257 minutes per unit. The learning rate is calculated to be approximately 95%.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}